# Fill in the middle: `IntervalRegistry.t_rebalance/1`

`IntervalRegistry` is a concurrent, process-backed interval store built on an
augmented **AVL interval tree**. Each node is a map of the shape
`%{s:, f:, id:, max_finish:, height:, left:, right:}` and is always constructed
through the helper `t_node/5`, which recomputes `height` and `max_finish` from
its children. Node ordering is by the key `{s, f, id}` (see `t_key/1`).

Your task is to implement the private helper `t_rebalance/1`, the single function
`t_insert/4` and `t_delete/4` call after every structural change to restore the
AVL balance invariant.

`t_rebalance/1` takes one tree `node` and returns a balanced node:

- Compute the node's balance factor with `t_bf/1` (which is
  `height(left) - height(right)`).
- If the balance factor is greater than `1`, the node is **left-heavy**:
  - If its left child is right-heavy (`t_bf(node.left) < 0`), first perform a
    left rotation on the left child (the Left-Right case): rebuild the node via
    `t_node/5` with `t_rotate_left(node.left)` as the new left child, keeping the
    same `s`, `f`, `id`, and right child.
  - Then return `t_rotate_right/1` of the (possibly updated) node.
- If the balance factor is less than `-1`, the node is **right-heavy** (mirror
  case):
  - If its right child is left-heavy (`t_bf(node.right) > 0`), first perform a
    right rotation on the right child (the Right-Left case): rebuild the node via
    `t_node/5` with `t_rotate_right(node.right)` as the new right child, keeping
    the same `s`, `f`, `id`, and left child.
  - Then return `t_rotate_left/1` of the (possibly updated) node.
- Otherwise the node is already balanced — return it unchanged.

Use only the existing helpers (`t_bf/1`, `t_node/5`, `t_rotate_left/1`,
`t_rotate_right/1`); do not add new functions or change any other code.

